---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';

const photos = Array.from({ length: 15 }, (_, i) => `tabor2019-${String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}.jpg`);
---

<Base title="Diaspora School Camp 2019" lang="en" description="Report on the 2019 Diaspora School Camp in Vancouver.">
  <div class="container container--narrow prose">
    <h1 class="page-title">Diaspora School Camp 2019</h1>

    <p>
      We first heard about the Diaspora School Camps in February 2019, at the
      Conference of Hungarian Schools Abroad in Budapest. Our school liked the idea
      so much that a few enthusiastic teachers and volunteers immediately got in
      touch with the Hungarian Scout Association in Exteris. The association was
      very open and helpful, so even though we had only five months, the Szent
      László School of Vancouver managed to organize the camp. We found a suitable
      venue, a dance teacher, and a cook. We put together the material for five
      hours of daily sessions at four levels. By May 31, 36 children had signed up.
      The camp ultimately became international — we were even joined from Seattle.
      And on July 22, at Camp Kanaka in Maple Ridge, the first Diaspora School Camp
      ever held in Canada opened its gates, organized by the Szent László Hungarian
      School.
    </p>
    <p>
      We spent five very rich days together in great spirits. In Ricsi and Anita we
      had two capable, proactive, dynamic, well-prepared helpers — we could not
      have imagined better ones.
    </p>
    <p>
      The 36 children polished their Hungarian language and literature skills in
      four groups. To our great joy, we managed to order an atlas for every child.
      The children browsed them eagerly, getting to know Hungary's geography,
      counties, and cities. The framing story this year was Ferenc Rákóczi II and
      his era, so the children — each at their own level, and in a playful way —
      also got a picture of this period of history.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most of the five hours of daily learning also took place through play,
      helped along by drama pedagogy and board games. After the lessons, dance,
      song, and craft activities coloured the camp's days.
    </p>
    <p>
      Many thanks to the Hungarian Scout Association in Exteris and to Gábor Szórád
      for their help in organizing our camp on such short notice. Thanks to the many
      volunteers — the teachers, the sports and craft session leaders, and everyone
      working in the background — that we could put all our resources into giving
      the children the richest, highest-quality week possible at the school camp.
      As the photo and video montage shows, we succeeded.
    </p>

    <iframe
      class="video-embed"
      src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/vWw3oGWouP8"
      title="Diaspora School Camp 2019 – video"
      allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
      allowfullscreen
    ></iframe>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="gallery">
      {photos.map((img, i) => (
        <a href={`/images/${img}`} target="_blank">
          <img src={`/images/${img}`} alt={`Diaspora School Camp 2019 – photo ${i + 1}`} loading="lazy" />
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
